and against Italian American culture that reflected the Catholic Church's discountenancing of homosexual love. Giannone vividly weaves his reflections on gay life in Greenwich Village and his spiritual journey as a gay man and Catholic into his experience of caring for the women of his family.In Hidden Giannone recounts a gripping religious conversion, drawing on the wisdom of the ancient desert mothers and fathers of Egypt and Palestine. Because he was raised a Catholic, the shift is not from nothing to something. Rather, it is away from the modeling power of institutional Christianity to the tempering influence of homosexuality on the Gospel. Gay or straight, so long as we remain hidden from ourselves, the true God remains hidden from us.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aCare of the sick. 0aCaringxReligious aspectsxCatholic Church. 0aCatholic gay menzNew York (State)zNew YorkvBiography. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311070729840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823241873zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823241873423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823241873.jpg  a978-3-11-070729-8  FUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK